{"id":"1703.00299","submitter":"Matthew Roberts","authors":"Simon C. Harris, Samuel G.G. Johnston and Matthew I. Roberts","title":"The coalescent structure of continuous-time Galton-Watson trees","comments":"57 pages, 6 figures. Substantial revision","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Take a continuous-time Galton-Watson tree. If the system survives until a\nlarge time $T$, then choose $k$ particles uniformly from those alive. What does\nthe ancestral tree drawn out by these $k$ particles look like? Some special\ncases are known but we give a more complete answer. We concentrate on\nnear-critical cases where the mean number of offspring is $1+\\mu/T$ for some\n$\\mu\\in\\mathbb{R}$, and show that a scaling limit exists as $T\\to\\infty$.\nViewed backwards in time, the resulting coalescent process is topologically\nequivalent to Kingman's coalescent, but the times of coalescence have an\ninteresting and highly non-trivial structure. The randomly fluctuating\npopulation size, as opposed to constant size populations where the Kingman\ncoalescent more usually arises, have a pronounced effect on both the results\nand the method of proof required. We give explicit formulas for the\ndistribution of the coalescent times, as well as a construction of the\ngenealogical tree involving a mixture of independent and identically\ndistributed random variables. In general subcritical and supercritical cases it\nis not possible to give such explicit formulas, but we highlight the special\ncase of birth-death processes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Mar 2017 13:59:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 24 Mar 2017 10:28:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 11 Sep 2017 12:50:30 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 13 Feb 2019 09:11:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-02-14"}
